WEBVTT

00:31.531 --> 00:34.952
[melancholy music playing]

00:34.952 --> 00:38.372
[bus engine humming]

00:50.092 --> 00:51.093
[bus exhaust blows]

01:24.001 --> 01:26.461
[indistinct chatter]

01:26.920 --> 01:32.217
[singing in Hindi]

01:53.989 --> 01:59.286
[engine whirring]

02:01.705 --> 02:02.664
[door squeaks]

02:11.757 --> 02:15.844
[motorcycle engines revving]

02:17.512 --> 02:21.058
-[indistinct chatter]
-[bell jingles]

02:23.727 --> 02:27.064
[country music playing]

02:40.410 --> 02:43.330
-What are you in town for, hon?
-Dakota Sioux powwow.

02:43.747 --> 02:45.248
No kidding. Hmm.

02:56.134 --> 02:57.386
[man] Hey, sweetheart,
can we get

02:57.386 --> 02:58.553
some service around here?

02:58.970 --> 03:01.890
You know, by afternoon there's
gonna be 300,000 bikers here

03:01.890 --> 03:05.268
for the Annual Blackhills
Bike Rally. You didn't know?

03:08.855 --> 03:11.566
No. No. Leave her alone.
Come on. Come on.

03:18.448 --> 03:19.908
You're Gloria Steinem.

03:20.700 --> 03:21.576
I am.

03:22.369 --> 03:24.704
[chuckles] It's her. I told you.

03:24.704 --> 03:25.914
Oh, wow.

03:26.289 --> 03:28.125
I wanna tell you
how much Ms magazine

03:28.125 --> 03:29.543
has meant to me over the years.

03:30.502 --> 03:34.881
We love your work, Ms. Steinem.
You changed our lives.

03:35.424 --> 03:37.592
That means a lot to me.
Thank you.

03:37.884 --> 03:39.052
Um. You see the...

03:39.678 --> 03:42.180
-the purple Harley out there?
-Mm-hmm.

03:42.556 --> 03:44.724
That big gorgeous one?

03:45.434 --> 03:46.476
That's mine.

03:47.477 --> 03:49.771
She always used to ride
behind me.

03:49.771 --> 03:51.982
Yeah. And I started reading
your magazine

03:51.982 --> 03:53.900
and-- and I decided
I wanted to take

03:53.900 --> 03:55.193
to the road on my own.

03:57.946 --> 04:01.700
[motorcycle engine revs]

04:15.297 --> 04:16.840
-[engine humming]
-[girl gasps]

04:18.341 --> 04:21.928
[rain pattering]

04:22.345 --> 04:25.807
[singing]
♪ Blue skies smiling at me ♪

04:26.892 --> 04:30.437
♪ Nothin' but blue skies
Do I see ♪

04:31.813 --> 04:36.109
-♪ Blue birds singin' a song ♪
-♪ Blue birds singin' a song ♪

04:36.693 --> 04:38.653
-♪ Nothing but blue birds ♪
-♪ Nothing but blue birds ♪

04:38.653 --> 04:40.197
-♪ All day long ♪
-♪ All day long ♪

04:41.823 --> 04:43.408
-[sighs]
-[Leo] Yeah.

04:43.700 --> 04:45.702
-[car door opens]
-[Leo whistling]

04:49.414 --> 04:50.415
[car door closes]

04:51.082 --> 04:52.042
[Leo grunts]

04:54.586 --> 04:55.504
[Leon groans]

04:56.671 --> 04:58.548
Okay. Yeah.

04:58.548 --> 05:00.884
-All good?
-Yeah. [sighs]

05:11.478 --> 05:13.313
[car horn honks]

05:14.940 --> 05:17.776
[dog barking]

05:21.238 --> 05:22.155
Voila.

05:22.614 --> 05:24.324
Who found us a jukebox
in the middle of nowhere?

05:24.699 --> 05:26.117
That would be you.

05:27.285 --> 05:28.537
It's, uh, just in case.

05:29.746 --> 05:31.998
[rain pattering]

05:37.796 --> 05:40.966
[telephone ringing]

05:45.595 --> 05:46.596
Hello?

05:47.847 --> 05:49.015
This is she.

05:51.351 --> 05:52.435
[sighs]

05:55.105 --> 05:57.357
Hmm. Yeah.

05:57.941 --> 05:59.234
I bet the roads are...

06:00.527 --> 06:04.197
uh, I know they probably have
a tight schedule, but...

06:05.323 --> 06:06.324
[sighs]

06:06.575 --> 06:07.492
Uh-huh.

06:24.384 --> 06:25.343
Papa!

06:26.970 --> 06:29.097
The Andrews Sisters
aren't coming.

06:32.100 --> 06:32.976
[sighs]

06:36.104 --> 06:37.188
[taps mic]

06:37.814 --> 06:39.065
All right.

06:39.399 --> 06:41.818
Now, I know you're all
a little disappointed,

06:42.068 --> 06:44.988
but we've got
the Andrews Sisters here.

06:44.988 --> 06:47.699
Right here on the jukebox.

06:48.116 --> 06:49.284
-[jukebox starts]
-[crowd groans]

06:50.994 --> 06:53.038
Yeah. And we know
it's the next best thing.

06:53.038 --> 06:57.917
So, let's get dancing.
I am your host Leo Steinemite.

06:57.917 --> 07:00.462
Let's make it dynamite!

07:01.087 --> 07:02.589
-["Sing Sing Sing" playing]
-Hit it.

07:02.589 --> 07:06.426
♪ Sing, sing, sing, sing
Everybody start to sing ♪

07:06.760 --> 07:10.764
♪ Ooh, now you're singin'
With a swing ♪

07:10.764 --> 07:14.768
♪ Sing, sing, sing, sing
Everybody start to sing ♪

07:14.768 --> 07:18.980
♪ Ooh, now you're singin'
With a swing ♪

07:24.736 --> 07:26.613
-[rain pattering]
-[Leo] Aw.

07:30.241 --> 07:32.827
[women giggling]

07:37.540 --> 07:40.210
[Leo] Whoa! [chuckles]

07:41.127 --> 07:42.504
♪ Come on and sing ♪

07:43.004 --> 07:44.798
[indistinct chatter]

07:45.840 --> 07:47.425
["(I'll Be With You)
In Apple Blossom Time" playing]

07:47.425 --> 07:49.719
♪ I'll be with you ♪

07:49.719 --> 07:54.265
♪ In apple blossom time ♪

07:55.809 --> 08:00.397
♪ I'll be with you ♪

08:00.397 --> 08:05.276
♪ To change your name to mine ♪

08:06.569 --> 08:11.116
♪ One day in May ♪

08:11.950 --> 08:17.038
♪ I'll come and say ♪

08:17.789 --> 08:21.751
-That was so much fun.
-Honey, look at you.

08:22.711 --> 08:23.712
[Gloria sighs]

08:24.170 --> 08:27.298
-I love dancing.
-Oh, you're soaked.

08:27.549 --> 08:31.261
Was that jukebox not the find
of the century? [chuckles]

08:31.720 --> 08:33.054
Why the long face?

08:33.972 --> 08:37.183
One summer storm wipes us out
for an entire month.

08:37.475 --> 08:39.894
You might as well
be playing Blackjack.

08:40.520 --> 08:42.480
[sighs]
Ruth, you worry too much.

08:43.898 --> 08:46.484
Gloria, Susanne,
it's time for bed.

08:54.033 --> 08:55.702
They're gonna repossess our car,
Leo,

08:55.702 --> 08:57.370
if we don't pay by the first
of the month.

08:57.829 --> 09:00.039
So we'll park it down the road,
no one will find it.

09:01.124 --> 09:04.085
[sighs, sniffles]

09:05.170 --> 09:07.881
We'll get out of town
in the fall. Huh?

09:08.423 --> 09:11.176
We'll make a bundle
doing the county auctions

09:11.176 --> 09:14.137
up and down the coast,
avoid the Michigan winter.

09:14.596 --> 09:18.558
Pass through Georgia for those
thin sugary pralines.

09:18.892 --> 09:21.436
Right? Drink ourselves
some fresh squeezed

09:21.436 --> 09:22.479
all you can drink oranges

09:22.937 --> 09:26.941
from those Florida roadside
stands and then head west

09:27.275 --> 09:31.196
for some California sunshine
and slabs of fresh salmon

09:31.196 --> 09:33.323
from a California smokehouse

09:33.323 --> 09:35.408
by the time we get back
next summer...

09:36.201 --> 09:37.952
we'll be on top again.

09:39.871 --> 09:40.955
[water dripping]

09:44.876 --> 09:46.753
Come here, kiddo,
new set of maps.

09:46.753 --> 09:48.213
[children playing]

09:52.801 --> 09:53.802
See?

09:54.302 --> 09:55.303
Okay.

09:55.595 --> 10:00.183
We go from here, here,
and then like this...

10:01.810 --> 10:03.353
all the way to...

10:05.897 --> 10:06.815
And then what?

10:07.273 --> 10:09.025
Well, you know what they say,
if you don't know

10:09.025 --> 10:12.070
what's gonna happen tomorrow,
could be wonderful.

10:23.873 --> 10:26.167
[car horn honking]

10:27.001 --> 10:28.211
Everybody in.

10:29.838 --> 10:33.591
-It's time to go, go, go.
-I'm not done with the dishes.

10:33.591 --> 10:36.052
Oh, leave the dishes, they'll be
clean by the time we get back.

10:36.052 --> 10:36.928
[Susanne] Mom.

10:37.345 --> 10:40.515
The winter automatically
sterilizes the germs.

10:50.608 --> 10:53.027
-Get the door for me.
-[Leo] Damn It!

10:56.072 --> 10:57.615
-Damn It!
-[barking]

10:57.866 --> 11:00.869
Come on, come on.
Right here, good boy.

11:01.870 --> 11:03.705
Why'd you have to go name
the dog Damn It?

11:03.705 --> 11:05.081
It's so embarrassing.

11:05.999 --> 11:08.418
It'd be more embarrassing
if you had a father who swore.

11:08.710 --> 11:09.961
[Leo] Don't you think?

11:17.635 --> 11:20.179
[Leo humming]

11:23.099 --> 11:24.809
[Leo continues humming]

11:24.809 --> 11:28.438
Gloria, you're gonna get
car sick reading in the back.

11:28.813 --> 11:30.398
I never get car sick.

11:30.398 --> 11:33.318
Put the book down for a minute
and look out of the window.

11:34.152 --> 11:36.446
I looked out the window
an hour ago.

11:37.030 --> 11:39.032
-[Ruth] Gloria.
-[Damn It panting]

11:39.032 --> 11:40.158
[Gloria sighs]

11:44.203 --> 11:45.872
[Damn It whines]

11:46.247 --> 11:49.709
Look at those houses. Slow down,
Papa, aren't they pretty?

11:50.126 --> 11:52.170
[children playing]

11:52.795 --> 11:55.006
Don't you wish we lived
in a house like that

11:55.006 --> 11:56.925
-all year round?
-Leo, we need to stay put

11:56.925 --> 11:59.177
for a while and let the girls
go to school.

11:59.510 --> 12:02.180
Gloria would be starting
the third grade by now.

12:02.180 --> 12:04.182
No.
Traveling is the best education.

12:04.807 --> 12:07.435
-It's the only education really.
-[train horn honks]

12:07.435 --> 12:09.187
[bells tolling]

12:10.688 --> 12:13.232
[train horn continues honking]

12:30.458 --> 12:32.710
[indistinct chatter]

12:39.467 --> 12:44.180
[boy speaking Hindi]

12:46.307 --> 12:49.185
[indistinct chatter]

12:53.940 --> 12:56.067
[speaking Hindi]

13:11.499 --> 13:15.545
[train engine chugging]

13:21.926 --> 13:22.927
[Ruth] Leo?

13:30.309 --> 13:31.853
I think this one is valuable.

13:33.229 --> 13:36.774
Can you do this without me?
I have a splitting headache.

13:36.774 --> 13:38.818
I need to go in for a lie down.

13:44.323 --> 13:46.200
[Leo] Right. There's no way
I'm paying 25 dollars

13:46.200 --> 13:47.618
for this cracked tea set.

13:48.453 --> 13:50.371
Five dollars is my final offer.

13:51.789 --> 13:52.957
-Twenty.
-Fifteen?

13:53.416 --> 13:54.417
Done.

14:02.050 --> 14:04.886
[Leo] We're gonna sell this
tea set to an antique dealer

14:04.886 --> 14:05.887
for 50 bucks.

14:06.179 --> 14:07.388
Mark my words.

14:07.847 --> 14:10.475
And all we need is ten dollars
for gas money

14:10.475 --> 14:12.268
to get us all the way
to Wyoming.

14:13.936 --> 14:15.730
[Leo] When we get to St. Louis
there's this one market,

14:15.730 --> 14:20.526
-all they sell is china...
-[man speaking Hindi]

14:25.656 --> 14:26.783
Chai, madam?

14:31.621 --> 14:33.206
[indistinct chatter]

14:36.167 --> 14:38.836
-[speaking Hindi]
-Only one rupee, madam.

14:46.761 --> 14:54.268
[speaking Hindi]

14:59.315 --> 15:02.026
-Please.
-Oh, please, no. No, no.

15:03.945 --> 15:05.154
Thank you.

15:09.033 --> 15:12.245
So you left the university
in New Delhi. Why?

15:13.246 --> 15:16.499
I wanna get out of the big city.
See the villages.

15:16.999 --> 15:18.584
What Gandhi talks about.

15:24.006 --> 15:29.220
[speaking Hindi]

15:30.221 --> 15:32.640
She is traveling in third class

15:32.890 --> 15:35.810
because,
this is ladies only carriage

15:36.435 --> 15:37.478
and safer.

15:38.104 --> 15:42.233
[speaking Hindi]

15:44.569 --> 15:47.572
But why aren't you traveling
in a private car

15:47.572 --> 15:49.365
like most of the foreigners?

15:49.907 --> 15:51.534
If I was in a car by myself,

15:51.534 --> 15:53.202
I wouldn't really even be
in India.

15:55.037 --> 15:56.414
And I wouldn't have met you.

15:56.873 --> 16:00.459
[speaking Hindi]

16:00.710 --> 16:03.004
[all laugh]

16:36.746 --> 16:39.123
[Ruth] This used to be
our beautiful farmhouse.

16:40.291 --> 16:41.918
Lots of land all around.

16:44.462 --> 16:46.672
Your granny was born here,
Gloria.

16:58.809 --> 17:00.353
[Ruth] Oh, good God.

17:25.878 --> 17:26.963
[Gloria] Come inside, Mom.

17:27.546 --> 17:28.798
You'll catch a cold.

17:35.221 --> 17:36.347
[man over TV]
Firemen drag their hoses

17:36.722 --> 17:39.767
11 stories up to reach
the fire on the 79th floor...

17:51.320 --> 17:53.114
So, where's your father
these days?

17:53.364 --> 17:55.825
-South America.
-South America?

17:56.117 --> 17:58.369
"Buying and selling opals
in Argentina.

17:58.369 --> 18:00.621
Sending you a money order, love,
your pop."

18:01.205 --> 18:02.290
[chuckles]

18:13.718 --> 18:14.802
Are you okay, Mom?

18:17.471 --> 18:18.889
I'm fine.

18:21.267 --> 18:24.562
Would you sign this check?
It's for the electric.

18:30.109 --> 18:32.028
And I-- I found these papers

18:32.028 --> 18:33.738
while I was looking
for your checkbook.

18:34.905 --> 18:36.032
What are they?

18:37.491 --> 18:40.036
Oh, it's nothing.
It's just my old writing

18:40.036 --> 18:41.704
when I used to work
at the newspaper.

18:43.956 --> 18:45.416
But it doesn't say your name.

18:45.416 --> 18:47.793
-It says Duncan McKenzie--
-McKenzie. That's me.

18:48.919 --> 18:51.505
Duncan McKenzie.
That's what I went by.

18:51.964 --> 18:54.258
That's the way it was for women
back then.

18:54.884 --> 18:55.885
Imagine.

18:58.304 --> 19:00.931
Well, why aren't you writing
anymore, Mom?

19:06.604 --> 19:07.855
Are you hungry?

19:09.023 --> 19:10.691
Do you want me to make you
a baloney sandwich

19:10.691 --> 19:12.318
with red onions and mayonnaise?

19:14.820 --> 19:16.405
No, thank you. I'm fine, dear.

19:16.864 --> 19:20.618
You just run off and play
or read whatever you like.

19:27.458 --> 19:29.335
Why are you tap dancing outside?

19:30.002 --> 19:31.504
It's too loud for my mother
inside.

19:32.713 --> 19:34.006
What's wrong with your mother?

19:35.758 --> 19:37.134
We don't have linoleum.

19:38.094 --> 19:39.387
We got linoleum.

19:40.471 --> 19:42.682
-[dog barks]
-[indistinct chatter]

19:44.975 --> 19:46.477
I've got an extra pair
of tap shoes.

19:46.936 --> 19:49.730
My big sister, Shirley,
she grew to size 12 this year.

19:49.730 --> 19:50.731
Wait there.

19:52.191 --> 19:53.609
-[man] Ruby?
-[Ruby] Hi, Papa.

19:55.820 --> 19:58.406
[song playing over radio]

19:58.781 --> 20:01.450
-[footsteps approaching]
-Come and sit down over here.

20:04.495 --> 20:06.956
[music playing over radio]

20:08.541 --> 20:10.042
Papa, can I change the station?

20:10.042 --> 20:11.377
-Yeah, go ahead.
-Just wait and watch.

20:13.921 --> 20:16.757
Now, here is
Count Basie and his orchestra.

20:17.633 --> 20:21.303
[jazz playing over radio]

20:25.516 --> 20:27.184
[shoes tapping]

20:32.940 --> 20:35.484
[man] She can tap a little bit.
[laughs]

20:37.987 --> 20:42.283
[indistinct chatter]

20:47.288 --> 20:48.581
[man] All right, now!

20:49.373 --> 20:51.041
Oh, what, you want to see?

20:52.334 --> 20:53.627
[man 2] Back at ya, huh.

20:53.919 --> 20:55.004
[man 3] Aw man.

20:56.046 --> 20:57.089
Look at that.

20:57.840 --> 20:58.883
[woman laughs]

20:59.216 --> 21:01.218
-[man 2] Hey, that's nice.
-[woman 1] You got it.

21:02.553 --> 21:03.637
[man 2 laughs]

21:05.639 --> 21:06.640
Yeah!

21:09.143 --> 21:11.187
-All right!
-Come now!

21:11.604 --> 21:12.480
Whoo!

21:14.899 --> 21:17.485
[laughs] I'll tell you what,

21:17.776 --> 21:19.987
you girls gonna tap dance
your way out of Toledo.

21:19.987 --> 21:21.238
Into the heart of America.

21:21.906 --> 21:24.366
[all cheer]

21:30.915 --> 21:32.082
[woman] That's my baby.

21:33.000 --> 21:35.586
[indistinct chatter]

21:37.296 --> 21:38.380
Yeah.

21:41.759 --> 21:44.303
-[bell dings]
-[man 3 laughing]

21:47.389 --> 21:48.390
-[radio clicks]
-[music stops]

21:48.682 --> 21:49.850
Can I help you?

21:49.850 --> 21:51.310
Is there a girl here named
Gloria?

21:55.731 --> 21:57.233
Your mama is looking
for you again.

21:58.651 --> 22:02.613
[engine revving]

22:15.417 --> 22:17.795
[man] Hollywood Boulevard
is a blaze of lights.

22:17.795 --> 22:18.712
Thousands of people...

22:19.046 --> 22:21.048
...♪ For you
Forget your troubles ♪

22:21.799 --> 22:23.467
♪ If you go in
through your... ♪

22:24.843 --> 22:26.720
[man] The green steam
calling me out

22:26.720 --> 22:28.639
in full force this evening.
We promised to...

22:28.931 --> 22:30.349
[indistinct chatter]

22:30.349 --> 22:32.476
[woman] Brand new tickets,
brand new spirits.

22:32.476 --> 22:34.937
[man] Lovely DeLove,
Jean Harlow.

22:35.187 --> 22:37.398
[shoes tapping]

23:23.736 --> 23:25.571
-[car door opens]
-[Gloria trembles]

23:26.447 --> 23:28.198
Where were you? [gasps]

23:31.285 --> 23:32.536
[yells] Where were you?

23:33.454 --> 23:35.456
I was so worried about you,
Gloria.

23:35.456 --> 23:36.373
I'm sorry, Mom.

23:38.250 --> 23:39.418
[Ruth panting]

23:40.794 --> 23:44.131
I saw German soldiers outside
and I couldn't find you.

23:44.131 --> 23:46.342
-[breathes heavily]
-There aren't any soldiers, Mom.

23:46.759 --> 23:48.427
I heard them outside.

23:48.927 --> 23:49.887
The war...

23:50.554 --> 23:52.014
There's no war, Mom.

23:52.014 --> 23:54.850
It's okay. It's just
those Bukowskis at it again.

23:56.644 --> 23:58.687
Did you forget
to take your Doc Howard's?

23:59.897 --> 24:01.231
I couldn't find it. [sobs]

24:02.107 --> 24:03.233
-Okay.
-[sniffles]

24:03.567 --> 24:06.403
-Okay.
-[trembles]

24:09.323 --> 24:11.700
[Ruth breathing heavily]

24:14.036 --> 24:15.329
[bottle rattling]

24:17.873 --> 24:18.832
Just one teaspoon.

24:25.756 --> 24:28.300
[pants]

24:56.245 --> 24:58.831
-[people clamoring]
-[brake squealing]

24:58.831 --> 24:59.998
[woman] This is your stop.

25:00.332 --> 25:03.001
-What's going on?
-I fear there are caste riots,

25:03.001 --> 25:04.336
if you go straight to
the Ashram,

25:04.336 --> 25:05.337
it should be safe there.

25:07.005 --> 25:08.132
Thank you.

25:08.132 --> 25:10.801
[indistinct chanting]

25:12.511 --> 25:14.555
[speaking Hindi]

25:20.686 --> 25:24.064
[people clamoring]

25:28.736 --> 25:30.612
[indistinct chatter]

25:32.906 --> 25:36.952
-Do you know the Ashram?
-[speaking Hindi]

26:04.605 --> 26:06.774
-[window clatter]
-Oh, hello?

26:12.571 --> 26:15.449
[chuckles] I've arranged to stay
in the guest house.

26:15.699 --> 26:16.909
Madam Gloria?

26:17.493 --> 26:19.203
-Yes, yes.
-Yes, hi.

26:19.495 --> 26:21.246
But I'm afraid everyone is gone.

26:21.246 --> 26:23.040
-Gone?
-Because of the riots,

26:23.040 --> 26:24.166
you cannot stay here.

26:25.417 --> 26:26.668
I leave today, you see?

26:28.128 --> 26:30.339
We must do what we can to help.

26:31.799 --> 26:33.717
You may come with me
if you like.

26:35.135 --> 26:36.428
-[cow moos]
-[laughs]

26:36.804 --> 26:38.722
-Where?
-Village to village.

26:39.681 --> 26:42.100
They need other women to listen
to their stories.

26:42.684 --> 26:45.187
Otherwise village women
will not tell what happen.

26:46.313 --> 26:47.356
They will stay silent.

26:48.106 --> 26:49.274
I see.

26:49.274 --> 26:50.859
[mooing]

26:50.859 --> 26:51.902
Would you like to come?

26:53.570 --> 26:55.447
Would I be out of place
as a foreigner?

26:56.281 --> 27:00.035
To a woman in rural village,
a white woman in sari

27:00.285 --> 27:02.621
will seem no stranger than a man
from New Delhi.

27:03.872 --> 27:05.874
So, would you like to come?

27:07.209 --> 27:08.126
Yes.

27:08.710 --> 27:10.003
-When?
-Now.

27:11.964 --> 27:14.716
-All right.
-Only the suitcase is too big.

27:15.342 --> 27:16.635
You're American, I think.

27:19.054 --> 27:21.056
-Yes.
-Can you travel light?

27:25.978 --> 27:28.981
[man chanting]

27:32.860 --> 27:36.321
[Gloria] I'm very interested
in how Gandhi made non-violence

27:36.321 --> 27:37.239
into a whole movement.

27:37.698 --> 27:40.242
We women taught Gandhi
everything he knows.

27:40.242 --> 27:41.743
[both laugh]

27:41.743 --> 27:46.039
Gandhi watched his mother
and aunties fight using Ahimsa.

27:46.540 --> 27:48.792
-Ahimsa?
-Means non-violence.

27:49.042 --> 27:50.419
[indistinct chatter]

27:50.836 --> 27:51.712
You will see.

27:52.170 --> 27:54.965
If you hope, people will change
how they live.

27:55.299 --> 27:57.384
First, you should know
how they live.

27:59.595 --> 28:00.721
[goat bleats]

28:03.640 --> 28:05.934
[speaking Hindi]

28:08.854 --> 28:13.150
[conversing in Hindi]

28:23.660 --> 28:27.581
[speaking Hindi]

28:32.294 --> 28:36.673
[conversing in Hindi]

28:45.474 --> 28:48.185
[speaking Hindi]

28:52.356 --> 28:55.651
[conversing in Hindi]

28:58.445 --> 29:00.572
[speaking Hindi]

29:00.572 --> 29:02.074
[women groan]

29:03.075 --> 29:04.117
[speaking Hindi]

29:04.618 --> 29:06.411
Her daughter was raped
in front of her.

29:07.037 --> 29:08.580
[speaking Hindi]

29:08.580 --> 29:10.040
[woman]
She could not do anything.

29:14.503 --> 29:15.504
[speaking Hindi]

29:15.921 --> 29:17.172
-She took her to hospital...
-[indistinct chatter]

29:23.762 --> 29:28.141
[speaking Hindi]

29:29.601 --> 29:34.022
[speaks foreign language]

29:34.898 --> 29:36.400
People don't speak about this.

29:49.037 --> 29:52.666
[speaking Hindi]

29:52.666 --> 29:57.421
[speaks foreign language]

30:03.802 --> 30:05.262
[speaking Hindi]

30:06.346 --> 30:09.850
[conversing in Hindi]

30:17.899 --> 30:18.859
[speaking Hindi]

30:35.584 --> 30:37.377
[shoes clacking]

31:06.740 --> 31:07.908
But I don't understand.

31:09.826 --> 31:11.036
What does my mother have?

31:12.788 --> 31:15.207
Anxiety, neurosis...

31:16.166 --> 31:19.544
-low self-esteem, agoraphobia--
-Her spirit is broken.

31:21.046 --> 31:22.756
That's a good a diagnosis
as any.

31:25.008 --> 31:27.511
It's been broken for as long
as I've known her.

31:28.553 --> 31:29.805
Before I was born.

31:38.230 --> 31:42.609
[chimes ringing]

31:44.611 --> 31:49.699
[indistinct chatter]

32:14.182 --> 32:17.853
-[indistinct chatter]
-[bell rings]

32:26.987 --> 32:27.946
[speaking foreign language]

32:36.288 --> 32:38.331
-Here madam.
-[speaking Hindi]

32:48.425 --> 32:49.968
[Leo] "Gloria,
here's a money order.

32:50.385 --> 32:52.637
When you're ready,
buy your passage home

32:52.637 --> 32:54.389
by train and boat, it's cheap.

32:54.681 --> 32:57.893
Then go out and purchase
the biggest star sapphire

32:57.893 --> 32:59.269
in Jaipur you can find.

32:59.728 --> 33:01.188
I'll meet you in San Francisco.

33:01.521 --> 33:03.982
When your boat docks,
we'll sell that sapphire

33:03.982 --> 33:07.694
for a profit that'll pay for us
to drive back east in style.

33:08.153 --> 33:11.489
Can't wait to see you.
Your pop, Steinemite."

33:11.865 --> 33:15.118
[indistinct chatter]

33:26.880 --> 33:31.551
-[car horn honking]
-[train bell dinging]

33:33.011 --> 33:34.179
[Leo clears throat]

33:37.057 --> 33:38.016
You look thin.

33:39.226 --> 33:42.604
-It's called healthy, Pop.
-Have another egg roll for me.

33:45.273 --> 33:46.399
Have you seen Mom?

33:48.026 --> 33:50.445
Susanne wrote and said
she's doing a little better.

33:52.322 --> 33:54.658
Holy moly this moo shu is...

33:54.658 --> 33:55.784
is out of this world.

33:56.701 --> 33:57.869
[Leo] Mm.

33:58.411 --> 34:00.330
-[Leo] Mm.
-[cutlery clattering]

34:00.664 --> 34:01.873
Did you get the...

34:04.292 --> 34:05.335
Hmm.

34:06.336 --> 34:08.338
-Is this what you had in mind?
-Fabulous.

34:11.800 --> 34:14.844
You-- you are a Steinem,
no doubt about it.

34:20.100 --> 34:21.101
I, uh...

34:21.810 --> 34:22.727
[Gloria laughs]

34:23.228 --> 34:24.145
[Leo clears throat]

34:25.647 --> 34:26.815
[Leo exhales]

34:28.566 --> 34:29.567
What's wrong?

34:33.822 --> 34:37.325
[Leo] Yeah, the star is a little
off kilter, not worth much.

34:38.118 --> 34:40.412
Well, you didn't say
it needed to be symmetrical.

34:42.622 --> 34:43.540
Don't worry, kid.

34:46.293 --> 34:48.545
So, how are we gonna get
to New York?

34:48.545 --> 34:50.630
I have enough gas money
to get us to Las Vegas.

34:50.630 --> 34:52.173
[chuckles] And then?

34:52.465 --> 34:54.843
Well, if you don't know
what's gonna happen tomorrow,

34:55.510 --> 34:58.054
-it could be wonderful.
-It could be wonderful.

34:58.054 --> 35:00.890
["Pennies From Heaven" playing]

35:00.890 --> 35:05.145
♪ And every time it rains
It rains pennies from heaven ♪

35:05.478 --> 35:06.938
♪ Shoo-be dooby ♪

35:06.938 --> 35:09.107
♪ Don't you know
Each cloud contains ♪

35:09.107 --> 35:10.734
♪ Pennies from heaven... ♪

35:10.734 --> 35:12.027
-♪ Shoo-be dooby ♪
-[machine clicks]

35:12.027 --> 35:13.653
[Leo]
Let's hit the one arm bandit.

35:14.029 --> 35:15.280
Beginners are queuing.

35:15.780 --> 35:17.699
Beginners are always lucky.

35:17.699 --> 35:18.658
-Trust me.
-All right.

35:18.658 --> 35:19.618
Okay. Here we go.

35:22.370 --> 35:23.288
Yeah.

35:26.708 --> 35:30.170
-Jackpot! [cheers]
-[coins clattering]

35:30.170 --> 35:32.130
[both laugh]

35:32.130 --> 35:35.091
I knew it! Oh, you tripled
my last 50 bucks.

35:35.967 --> 35:38.970
Jesus, Pop.
That was your last 50 bucks?

35:38.970 --> 35:41.348
Oh, you only live once. Or less.

35:41.348 --> 35:44.225
["Pennies From Heaven"
continues playing]

35:50.982 --> 35:53.401
♪ And you'll find
Your fortune fallin' ♪

35:53.860 --> 35:55.278
♪ All over town ♪

35:55.278 --> 35:56.529
♪ There'll be pennies
From heaven.. ♪

35:56.821 --> 35:59.949
We're gonna run out of gas
in approximately three miles.

36:00.825 --> 36:02.660
-Open that glove compartment.
-[song ends]

36:05.872 --> 36:08.375
Yeah. Put on the nicest bracelet
you can find.

36:11.878 --> 36:12.837
[jewelry clattering]

36:13.838 --> 36:14.964
Add a ring.

36:18.885 --> 36:20.095
Yeah, looking classy.

36:23.598 --> 36:26.309
I've never sold any of my
jewelry before.

36:26.309 --> 36:29.813
But my father and I find
ourselves in a terrible pickle.

36:31.356 --> 36:32.690
This is a family heirloom.

36:33.983 --> 36:35.110
[Gloria sighs]

36:46.454 --> 36:47.497
[Gloria exhales]

36:48.415 --> 36:49.416
[ringing]

36:56.589 --> 36:57.549
[sighs]

36:57.882 --> 36:59.259
♪ Double your pleasure ♪

36:59.551 --> 37:01.136
♪ Double your fun ♪

37:01.136 --> 37:03.972
♪ Doublemint, Doublemint
Doublemint gum ♪

37:03.972 --> 37:06.224
Aye, criminy.
Will you listen to that?

37:06.683 --> 37:10.895
I sent my slogan in a year ago
for that darn brand.

37:11.604 --> 37:14.232
[sighs] Double the flavor,
double the fun,

37:14.232 --> 37:16.025
you know, with Doublemint,
Doublemint gum.

37:16.025 --> 37:19.696
Fa, fa, flavor, fun.
Alliteration.

37:20.155 --> 37:22.699
And it's two Doublemints,
not three, for God sakes, two.

37:23.408 --> 37:26.661
I think it was double good,
twice.

37:26.661 --> 37:27.787
Yeah, well, it...

37:29.080 --> 37:30.707
[Leo] Yeah, slogans are tough.

37:30.999 --> 37:33.960
You send them in registered
mail to the ad agencies.

37:33.960 --> 37:36.045
And then you cross your fingers
that the bastards

37:36.045 --> 37:37.297
don't steal the ideas.

37:42.010 --> 37:43.178
I'm on a five, Harry.

37:43.178 --> 37:44.637
Can you make me
a pastrami on rye?

37:45.889 --> 37:48.183
-I love New York.
-[Leo] Well...

37:49.184 --> 37:50.810
if you can't find a job writing
you can always...

37:50.810 --> 37:52.562
-[bell dings]
-...fall back on your dancing.

37:52.562 --> 37:55.273
Sure, Pop.
You want me to be a Rockette?

37:55.648 --> 37:57.859
I know you wanna be a journalist
like your mother,

37:57.859 --> 38:00.570
but if you can't find work using
your fingers at a typewriter

38:01.112 --> 38:02.697
you can always use those legs.
Hmm?

38:03.114 --> 38:04.032
[chuckles]

38:04.491 --> 38:06.784
I read in Variety,
there's even a chorus line

38:06.784 --> 38:09.662
looking for five Beta-Kappa
girls over five-foot seven

38:09.662 --> 38:11.915
to dance in an outfit
called the High-Five Betas.

38:12.332 --> 38:13.333
That's you.

38:14.167 --> 38:15.668
I've got an interview
in ten minutes.

38:16.711 --> 38:20.006
-Wish me luck. See you at 6:00?
-Yeah. I'm on my way out.

38:20.006 --> 38:21.591
I got an auction in Jersey later

38:21.591 --> 38:23.176
then down to New Orleans
the day after.

38:24.844 --> 38:26.763
-Okay. [kisses]
-[Leo kisses]

38:27.472 --> 38:29.766
Remember, those desk jobs
can fatten your ankles.

38:31.100 --> 38:33.436
-Us Steinems like to move.
-Hmm.

38:34.270 --> 38:35.271
Sure do.

38:36.105 --> 38:38.775
[indistinct chatter]

38:48.243 --> 38:49.494
[car horn honking]

38:49.869 --> 38:53.289
-[typewriter keys clacking]
-[telephone ringing]

38:53.289 --> 38:56.000
-I'm here to see Mr. Anderson.
-He's back office.

38:59.254 --> 39:00.755
[Gloria sighs]

39:05.552 --> 39:08.805
Hmm, I see you've read
some stuff at college, but...

39:09.889 --> 39:12.183
[sighs] ...listen,
here at the magazine,

39:12.183 --> 39:13.601
we hire girls that do
the research

39:13.601 --> 39:15.019
-and the men write.
-Why is that?

39:15.019 --> 39:16.271
It's just the w--

39:17.730 --> 39:18.690
You're right.

39:19.732 --> 39:20.650
Why is that?

39:23.027 --> 39:25.780
Okay. So, what do you wanna
write about?

39:27.282 --> 39:28.157
I, uh...

39:28.616 --> 39:29.993
I-- I just returned

39:29.993 --> 39:31.786
from two years
traveling in India.

39:31.786 --> 39:35.623
The experiences and the stories
I saw and heard are amazing

39:35.623 --> 39:37.458
-and I would just love to--
-Look. [sighs]

39:37.458 --> 39:38.793
I'm gonna try you out

39:38.793 --> 39:40.753
on a fashion assignment.
[exhales]

39:59.022 --> 40:00.523
[Gloria] American women

40:00.857 --> 40:03.318
explain an advertising man
happily,

40:03.651 --> 40:05.236
-have gone absolutely...
-[typewriter keys clack]

40:05.236 --> 40:07.363
...out of their minds
from the knee down.

40:13.328 --> 40:16.623
[man] Good job, Gloria,
and it's funny.

40:17.332 --> 40:19.667
Rare to see a woman writer
with a sense of humor.

40:20.001 --> 40:21.794
Thanks. I was thinking...

40:22.587 --> 40:24.631
what about a profile
on Mayor Lindsay?

40:24.631 --> 40:26.090
What about a profile
of his wife?

40:26.090 --> 40:27.800
I'm sure she's very interesting.

40:28.343 --> 40:30.094
But as a general rule,
I'm more interested

40:30.094 --> 40:31.471
-in politicians.
-General rule.

40:31.471 --> 40:32.972
You're too young
to have general rules.

40:32.972 --> 40:35.516
Look. You're nothing
like our lady readers,

40:35.516 --> 40:38.937
but you're female, so try
to put yourself in their place

40:38.937 --> 40:40.271
for this next assignment.

40:41.064 --> 40:42.690
Spice it up
with some of your wit.

40:43.191 --> 40:44.484
We need it tomorrow morning.

40:45.652 --> 40:48.154
You can use Percy's desk.
He's out on assignment.

40:51.949 --> 40:55.912
[indistinct chatter]

40:59.082 --> 41:00.166
-Gloria?
-[telephone ringing]

41:00.416 --> 41:01.751
-It's Gloria, right?
-[man] Good teaser.

41:01.751 --> 41:03.336
Uh. The coffee's out.
Could you make some more?

41:03.336 --> 41:05.129
-[man] Here you go.
-Just a second.

41:05.129 --> 41:08.925
-[typewriter keys clacking]
-[telephone ringing]

41:11.177 --> 41:14.305
[indistinct chatter]

41:19.686 --> 41:23.731
-Yeah. I'll-- I'll hold.
-[employees laugh]

41:23.731 --> 41:25.024
[man] Yup. Right here.

41:30.780 --> 41:33.658
[typewriter keys clacking]

42:21.748 --> 42:23.249
-Here it is.
-Thanks, hon.

42:23.583 --> 42:25.001
Oh, also, Gloria...

42:26.919 --> 42:28.838
would you mind... [sighs]

42:28.838 --> 42:30.548
...mailing these letters
and then...

42:33.342 --> 42:35.887
you can meet me at the Hilton,
Suite 910.

42:46.647 --> 42:49.859
-[typewriter keys clacking]
-[telephone ringing]

42:49.859 --> 42:53.780
[song playing over radio]

42:54.071 --> 42:55.615
[Gloria]
A hot fudge sundae, please.

42:56.407 --> 42:57.492
How about some eggs first?

42:58.534 --> 43:00.203
-No.
-No? Okay.

43:00.912 --> 43:02.038
Coming right up.

43:03.122 --> 43:06.209
One hot fudge sundae
for breakfast.

43:06.209 --> 43:07.460
With whipped cream on that.

43:08.586 --> 43:13.091
[song playing over radio]

43:17.804 --> 43:19.222
I just quit a job.

43:20.848 --> 43:22.099
You want a cherry on top?

43:23.392 --> 43:24.435
Sure.

43:26.562 --> 43:29.774
-Eat your vegetables, Gloria.
-I'm not hungry.

43:32.151 --> 43:35.029
Sometimes you're hungry
for one thing and not another.

43:35.029 --> 43:36.739
[music playing]

43:37.114 --> 43:38.115
Leo!

43:39.575 --> 43:41.744
-[Gloria sighs, grunts]
-[bunny 1] Here.

43:42.161 --> 43:45.498
[indistinct chatter]

43:47.166 --> 43:49.252
[groans, exhales]

43:49.502 --> 43:51.170
Oh, you got to stuff it, Marie.

43:52.672 --> 43:56.884
-Stuff it?
-Here. Just in and up.

43:57.635 --> 44:00.179
No, don't use dry cleaning bags
they'll make you sweat.

44:00.763 --> 44:03.558
-You can use Kotex pads.
-Work it up bunny tails.

44:05.184 --> 44:06.769
[laughs]

44:08.729 --> 44:09.772
Poor little bunny.

44:19.740 --> 44:23.327
-[indistinct chatter]
-[woman clicks tongue]

44:30.835 --> 44:32.003
Bend over
at the waist, sweetheart.

44:32.545 --> 44:33.462
A little more.

44:34.881 --> 44:36.674
-[bunny 2] You got to smile.
-[camera shutter clicks]

44:36.674 --> 44:38.718
They give us demerits
if we don't smile.

44:39.218 --> 44:40.303
Demerits?

44:40.303 --> 44:42.430
Yeah.
Pay cuts if you don't smile.

44:42.763 --> 44:44.473
If you don't fit
into your costume.

44:44.473 --> 44:46.350
Or if we don't do
the bunny dip while serving.

44:47.143 --> 44:48.144
The bunny dip?

44:48.519 --> 44:49.604
Like so.

44:50.605 --> 44:52.231
-You'll get the hang of it.
-[chuckles]

44:53.149 --> 44:54.817
Oh, and one more thing,
little one,

44:54.817 --> 44:56.402
don't sleep with the customers.

44:56.986 --> 44:58.654
Even if they have
a member's key.

45:08.205 --> 45:10.416
[indistinct chatter]

45:11.626 --> 45:13.252
[footsteps approaching]

45:14.921 --> 45:16.714
Marie, you okay in there?

45:18.633 --> 45:21.052
-They need us upstairs, pronto.
-[Gloria] Okay.

45:25.640 --> 45:27.683
[man] Yeah.
She may need to go forward.

45:27.683 --> 45:28.768
[woman] Seriously.

45:28.768 --> 45:30.227
-Whatever you want.
-He's always...

45:30.227 --> 45:33.356
Oh, no, they walked out
onto the sidewalk there,

45:33.356 --> 45:34.565
really, I...

45:34.565 --> 45:36.275
-Yes.
-And... [laughs] Unbelievable.

45:36.525 --> 45:39.487
[indistinct chatter]

46:01.258 --> 46:05.012
[Gloria] It's been two weeks.
I still haven't been paid yet.

46:05.012 --> 46:06.514
That's because we're still
in training.

46:07.181 --> 46:08.724
-Is that normal?
-[utensils clattering]

46:08.724 --> 46:10.267
Some bunnies train
for three weeks

46:10.267 --> 46:11.310
with no pay at all.

46:11.811 --> 46:14.647
Lipstick on the glasses again.
Who's not doing their job?

46:14.647 --> 46:18.025
I've been working nine hours
straight with no break.

46:18.025 --> 46:20.319
-My feet are killing me.
-Is that even legal?

46:20.945 --> 46:22.363
What's legal got to do with it?

46:23.698 --> 46:24.615
[laughs]

46:25.157 --> 46:26.867
Have you had
your medical exam yet?

46:28.035 --> 46:29.036
[Gloria] What?

46:30.621 --> 46:32.373
-[bunny 3] Here you go.
-Thank you.

46:33.040 --> 46:35.209
They want to make sure
you don't have any diseases...

46:36.168 --> 46:37.086
down there.

46:37.461 --> 46:39.922
Danny, can I get a scotch
and two martinis?

46:39.922 --> 46:40.923
Make 'em dry.

46:41.549 --> 46:45.511
-Maybe we ought to join a union.
-[scoffs] Keep dreaming, sister.

46:49.306 --> 46:51.684
[music playing]

46:52.059 --> 46:53.185
[telephone ringing]

46:53.185 --> 46:54.979
"What really goes on
in their glamorous

46:54.979 --> 46:56.022
and exciting world,

46:56.689 --> 46:59.358
to find out Show Magazine
chose a writer who combines

46:59.358 --> 47:01.444
the hidden qualities
of a Phi Beta Kappa

47:01.444 --> 47:03.946
magna cum laude
graduate of Smith College

47:03.946 --> 47:05.614
-[man] Well, tell him...
-...with the more obvious ones

47:05.614 --> 47:07.074
of an ex-dancer
and beauty queen."

47:07.742 --> 47:10.077
Where is she? Where is she?

47:12.496 --> 47:14.123
Great job. You sold
thousands of magazines

47:14.123 --> 47:15.583
and now we got a lawsuit
on our hands.

47:15.583 --> 47:19.086
-Oh, Jesus.
-No, it's great. Publicity.

47:19.086 --> 47:20.796
-[telephone ringing]
-Selling like hotcakes,

47:20.796 --> 47:21.881
really great.

47:23.215 --> 47:24.842
I got a call for you, Gloria,
line two.

47:25.092 --> 47:28.471
[indistinct chatter]

47:29.305 --> 47:30.264
-Hello.
-[man] Write another word

47:30.723 --> 47:32.141
about Playboy
and you'll never work again.

47:32.600 --> 47:34.268
We'll hit you
with so many lawsuits

47:34.268 --> 47:35.644
you won't be able to
stand up straight

47:35.644 --> 47:36.896
in high heels or flats.

47:38.731 --> 47:41.859
-[all laugh]
-[man] The longest ears.

47:42.943 --> 47:44.445
[Leon] Hey, Gloria.

47:45.029 --> 47:46.238
How about next time
going undercover

47:46.238 --> 47:47.364
in the porno business?

47:48.365 --> 47:50.284
[Leon snorting] Just kiddin'.

47:52.286 --> 47:54.288
You know, you'd look cute
as a bunny, Leon.

47:54.288 --> 47:55.247
-[all cheer]
-Yeah.

47:55.831 --> 47:58.375
The costumes are so tight
that they'd give a man cleavage.

47:58.375 --> 48:00.044
-[people laugh]
-Then you could look at yourself

48:00.044 --> 48:01.128
in the mirror all day

48:01.128 --> 48:02.880
instead of staring
at the secretaries

48:02.880 --> 48:04.340
on your lunch break.

48:04.340 --> 48:05.925
[all laugh]

48:07.843 --> 48:09.720
-You wanted to see me.
-Come in.

48:10.805 --> 48:13.557
Publishing house called,
wants to make "A Bunny's Tale"

48:13.557 --> 48:16.185
into a full-length book.
What do you say?

48:17.561 --> 48:18.562
No, thank you.

48:19.939 --> 48:22.399
-It's good money.
-I don't care. I'm a writer.

48:22.983 --> 48:25.486
If I publish that book,
I'll be a bunny forever.

48:43.754 --> 48:47.049
No, those are too big.
They hide your beautiful face.

48:49.718 --> 48:50.886
They're perfect.

48:52.096 --> 48:55.307
[engine revs]

49:06.277 --> 49:07.319
-In there.
-Thank you.

49:07.736 --> 49:09.071
[nurse] Let's get you
a little more comfortable here.

49:11.532 --> 49:13.159
You doing all right?
Let me just pull that off.

49:14.994 --> 49:15.953
[nurse] Great.

49:18.455 --> 49:20.457
-Gloria.
-How are you, Mom?

49:20.457 --> 49:22.585
Oh, let's not talk about me.

49:23.043 --> 49:24.628
Now, look at this.

49:25.546 --> 49:27.882
[chuckles] One of the nurses
gave it to me.

49:28.132 --> 49:29.758
I was hoping
you wouldn't see it.

49:29.758 --> 49:30.718
Why not?

49:30.718 --> 49:32.052
I don't know. It's just...

49:33.387 --> 49:36.223
It doesn't seem to matter
why I was a bunny.

49:37.308 --> 49:39.602
It doesn't seem to matter
that I was exposing

49:39.602 --> 49:41.187
horrific working conditions.

49:41.979 --> 49:45.566
All that seems to matter
to people is that I was a bunny.

49:46.275 --> 49:48.611
I wish I'd never put on
that stupid outfit.

49:53.741 --> 49:56.327
So, people saw you as a bunny,
so what?

49:58.746 --> 50:00.080
You're a writer.

50:01.874 --> 50:04.877
You have a real byline.

50:05.711 --> 50:06.754
[Ruth] Look at that.

50:09.340 --> 50:14.220
I'm so proud of you, Gloria.
This is important journalism.

50:15.179 --> 50:18.974
Those women in bunny outfits,
they're gonna thank you one day.

50:18.974 --> 50:20.726
Mom, before you met Pop,

50:20.726 --> 50:23.103
you were writing serious stuff
all the time.

50:26.815 --> 50:30.778
If I pressed and asked her,
"Why didn't you leave?

50:32.404 --> 50:35.950
Why didn't you take my sister
and go to New York and write?

50:35.950 --> 50:38.244
Do what you wanted to do."
She would say it didn't matter.

50:40.329 --> 50:42.414
That she was lucky
to have my sister and me.

50:44.083 --> 50:46.085
And if you'd pressed
hard enough, she'd have said,

50:46.752 --> 50:50.089
"If I left, you never would've
been born."

50:57.471 --> 50:59.098
I never had the courage to say,

51:01.308 --> 51:03.143
"But you would've been born
instead."

51:25.874 --> 51:27.668
[sighs]

51:44.685 --> 51:46.270
-[indistinct chatter]
-[telephone ringing]

51:46.270 --> 51:47.521
[Ruth]
Martin Luther King

51:47.521 --> 51:49.273
is leading a civil rights march
on Washington.

51:49.940 --> 51:52.026
-I wanna cover it.
-[man] Love the glasses.

51:52.818 --> 51:54.320
Gloria, for better or worse,

51:54.320 --> 51:55.904
this bunny article put you
on the map.

51:56.322 --> 51:58.365
It can write your ticket
but this is not a good idea.

51:58.365 --> 51:59.450
I think it is.

52:00.200 --> 52:02.995
It'll be a massive campaign
against discrimination

52:02.995 --> 52:04.955
for new Federal laws, for jobs.

52:04.955 --> 52:06.540
No, this march
will probably amount

52:06.540 --> 52:08.792
to a handful of people
and be a complete bust.

52:08.792 --> 52:10.919
[chuckles] Really? This is huge.

52:10.919 --> 52:12.588
There are civil rights marches
out there

52:12.588 --> 52:15.090
who are being beaten, jailed,
and even murdered in the South.

52:15.591 --> 52:16.759
Some with police collusion.

52:16.759 --> 52:17.968
The White House is saying
we'll turn off

52:17.968 --> 52:18.927
the moderates in congress,

52:19.261 --> 52:20.804
who are needed to pass
the Civil Rights Act.

52:20.804 --> 52:21.805
Okay.

52:24.975 --> 52:27.394
Then what about that profile
on James Baldwin?

52:27.394 --> 52:28.437
Great.

52:29.229 --> 52:30.981
He's gonna be at the march on
Washington.

52:31.273 --> 52:33.442
I don't want you
at the march on Washington.

52:33.442 --> 52:34.318
It's gonna be too dangerous.

52:34.651 --> 52:36.445
You wanna do a story on Baldwin,
fine, great.

52:36.445 --> 52:38.489
Just wait until he gets back
from DC.

52:40.449 --> 52:41.700
[sighs]

52:43.619 --> 52:47.498
[telephone ringing]

52:48.791 --> 52:50.292
-Hello?
-[Susanne] I've been trying

52:50.292 --> 52:53.754
-to reach you for a week.
-[sighs] Susanne, I'm...

52:54.546 --> 52:55.756
I'm so sorry.

52:56.507 --> 52:58.842
-I've been on the road non-stop.
-It's dad.

52:59.551 --> 53:02.721
He's had an accident
on the highway in California.

53:03.055 --> 53:04.932
-How serious is it?
-It's bad.

53:05.224 --> 53:06.850
But they say
he'll pull through.

53:07.226 --> 53:09.395
Okay. Thank God.

53:09.895 --> 53:13.107
He's in the hospital.
He'll probably be out in a week

53:13.107 --> 53:15.484
and then he'll have
all kinds of rehab.

53:15.943 --> 53:19.655
Listen, Gloria, I can't fly
out there right now.

53:20.280 --> 53:23.242
The kids are starting school
and-- Can you go?

53:24.243 --> 53:27.413
I know you're working, but--
but could you go?

53:27.830 --> 53:30.249
In a week.
He should be out by then.

53:30.833 --> 53:31.834
Of course.

53:36.672 --> 53:38.298
[announcer]

53:38.590 --> 53:40.634
Paging Ms. Gloria Steinem.

53:40.634 --> 53:42.428
Please pick up
a white courtesy phone.

53:42.803 --> 53:44.513
Paging Ms. Gloria Steinem.

53:44.513 --> 53:46.640
Please pick up
a white courtesy phone.

53:48.267 --> 53:54.106
[sobs]

54:14.501 --> 54:15.502
[sniffles]

54:19.798 --> 54:21.467
[footsteps approaching]

54:22.759 --> 54:23.886
[bell dings]

54:34.730 --> 54:36.273
Why was there no family here?

54:37.357 --> 54:40.611
-I got here as soon as I could.
-He was here alone for a week.

54:41.528 --> 54:44.740
His death was caused
by gushing traumatic ulcers,

54:44.740 --> 54:47.117
not from the crash itself,
but from stress.

54:47.868 --> 54:48.744
Despair.

54:49.953 --> 54:52.414
I'm sorry. Please excuse me.

55:18.315 --> 55:19.983
I don't know
why I didn't go right away.

55:21.527 --> 55:22.986
Because you were afraid
if you went,

55:22.986 --> 55:24.112
you'd never come back

55:24.947 --> 55:27.824
and end up caring for him,
like you did for your mother.

55:29.952 --> 55:31.537
That's shit and you know it.

55:42.297 --> 55:46.552
[cries]

55:54.226 --> 55:55.352
[trembles]

55:57.896 --> 55:58.981
[exhales]

56:21.003 --> 56:24.172
[bus engines revving]

56:25.132 --> 56:29.678
[indistinct chatter]

56:46.653 --> 56:48.989
-Lemonade?
-Oh, thank you.

56:49.656 --> 56:50.699
You're welcome.

56:51.700 --> 56:53.660
It's gonna be a long hot day.

56:54.661 --> 56:56.288
You know, I worked in Washington

56:56.288 --> 56:57.706
during
the Truman administration.

56:58.373 --> 57:00.959
In the same room
as white clerks. Hmm.

57:01.293 --> 57:04.296
But segregated behind a screen.
Couldn't protest then.

57:04.671 --> 57:06.506
So, here I am today.

57:07.841 --> 57:11.470
[crowd] Now, now, now.

57:11.887 --> 57:13.263
That's Dorothy Height,

57:13.263 --> 57:14.765
-up on the speaker's platform.
-[indistinct speech]

57:15.098 --> 57:17.559
She's head of the National
Council of Negro Women.

57:18.185 --> 57:20.228
-[man] In the history...
-But why isn't she speaking?

57:20.479 --> 57:22.731
-...of this nation.
-And where's Ella Baker

57:22.731 --> 57:25.067
who trained all the
SNCC young people?

57:25.067 --> 57:28.362
-Oh, Mama. Don't go on.
-Or-- Or Fannie Lou Hamer.

57:29.154 --> 57:31.782
She got beat up in jail
and then sterilized

57:31.782 --> 57:33.158
in a Mississippi Hospital

57:33.158 --> 57:35.535
when she went in
for something else entirely.

57:36.828 --> 57:38.080
That's what happens.

57:38.330 --> 57:40.749
We supposed to give birth
to field hands

57:40.749 --> 57:43.085
when they need them
and not when they don't.

57:44.002 --> 57:45.629
My grandmother was dirt poor.

57:46.630 --> 57:50.926
She got paid 75 dollars
for every live birth.

57:51.968 --> 57:53.804
Difference between her
and Fannie Lou

57:53.804 --> 57:54.930
is farm equipment.

57:56.014 --> 57:58.308
They didn't need
many field hands anymore.

58:00.519 --> 58:03.939
I think I just might have a word
with my state delegation leader.

58:03.939 --> 58:05.774
You always have to make a fuss.

58:06.274 --> 58:08.193
That's right, I do.

58:10.278 --> 58:12.239
-Excuse me.
-[man] ...while we are not.

58:15.617 --> 58:18.453
Excuse me.
Why are there no women speakers?

58:18.787 --> 58:20.747
Oh, Mahalia Jackson
and Marian Anderson

58:20.747 --> 58:21.998
gonna be singing
in just a minute.

58:22.249 --> 58:23.542
Singing ain't speaking.

58:24.626 --> 58:26.795
Excuse me. Excuse me.

58:27.045 --> 58:28.380
[indistinct speech continues]

58:28.672 --> 58:30.006
What you just did,

58:30.006 --> 58:31.091
-that was bold.
-[exhales]

58:31.383 --> 58:32.300
It was nothing much.

58:34.261 --> 58:36.513
Then why do I always end up
giving my suggestions

58:36.513 --> 58:39.558
to the man on my left, so he can
take them to the man in charge?

58:40.976 --> 58:42.018
This guy on my left

58:42.018 --> 58:43.854
will be taken more seriously
than me.

58:44.563 --> 58:45.564
That simple.

58:46.273 --> 58:47.441
You white women.

58:48.066 --> 58:50.152
If you don't stand up
for yourselves,

58:50.444 --> 58:52.279
how you gonna stand up
for anybody else?

58:52.279 --> 58:53.613
[crowd agreeing]

58:53.613 --> 58:56.241
[man] We will now be blessed
with a solo...

58:56.241 --> 58:58.785
-Mahalia is about to sing.
-...by Mahalia Jackson.

58:58.785 --> 58:59.995
[crowd cheering]

58:59.995 --> 59:05.959
♪ I've ♪

59:06.293 --> 59:10.046
♪ Been 'buked ♪

59:12.090 --> 59:14.760
♪ And I've ♪

59:15.886 --> 59:19.431
♪ Been scorned ♪

59:22.309 --> 59:27.731
♪ I've ♪

59:29.483 --> 59:30.942
♪ Been... ♪

59:31.234 --> 59:34.654
[siren wailing]

59:34.946 --> 59:37.949
Jack told me the secret
to interviewing Bobby Kennedy.

59:37.949 --> 59:39.326
-Jack?
-Jack Newfield

59:39.326 --> 59:40.410
from The Village Voice.

59:41.328 --> 59:44.039
He said, um, Bobby
only answers questions

59:44.039 --> 59:46.291
if he thinks the reporter
doesn't know the subject

59:46.291 --> 59:47.918
or better yet, even disagrees,

59:47.918 --> 59:50.420
so-- so we're gonna
have to pretend

59:50.420 --> 59:52.380
we don't know the answers
to our questions.

59:53.965 --> 59:55.425
You know, Mr. Bennett,
that every year,

59:55.425 --> 59:57.511
there's a pretty girl
who comes to New York

59:57.511 --> 59:59.679
and pretends to be a writer
before she gets married.

1:00:00.347 --> 1:00:03.850
Well, Gloria
is this year's pretty girl.

1:00:05.435 --> 1:00:06.937
[both laugh]

1:00:10.190 --> 1:00:12.400
You know what,
you can say what you want,

1:00:12.400 --> 1:00:14.194
but some of us
are actually becoming the man

1:00:14.194 --> 1:00:15.612
we thought we wanted to marry.

1:00:19.783 --> 1:00:20.992
Did you say something?

1:00:21.868 --> 1:00:24.913
I didn't say anything.
Why didn't I object?

1:00:24.913 --> 1:00:27.207
-Get out and slam the door.
-No, no, you will.

1:00:27.207 --> 1:00:28.959
You will and--
and plenty of times,

1:00:28.959 --> 1:00:30.544
like, lots of times.

1:00:30.544 --> 1:00:32.587
Speaking your mind
will get you in deep trouble.

1:00:33.630 --> 1:00:34.631
Right?

1:00:37.884 --> 1:00:38.760
[chuckles]

1:00:40.053 --> 1:00:42.430
Love the Bobby piece.
You're a good writer, Gloria.

1:00:43.515 --> 1:00:45.267
In fact, you write like a man.

1:00:47.060 --> 1:00:48.103
Is that a compliment?

1:00:48.854 --> 1:00:49.813
-Funny.
-Listen, I've...

1:00:50.689 --> 1:00:51.898
I've done the profiles.

1:00:52.524 --> 1:00:55.735
Bobby Kennedy, Baldwin, Bellow,
Dorothy Parker,

1:00:55.735 --> 1:00:57.612
I even did
the Marco Fontaine piece

1:00:57.612 --> 1:00:59.197
about the dancer I couldn't be.

1:01:00.490 --> 1:01:01.741
[sighs] Max, I...

1:01:02.492 --> 1:01:04.286
I want to write
about the women's movement.

1:01:04.744 --> 1:01:06.079
-What movement?
-I wanna write

1:01:06.079 --> 1:01:07.914
about why the face of congress
is male,

1:01:08.373 --> 1:01:10.166
and the face of welfare
is female.

1:01:10.166 --> 1:01:13.420
Why homemakers are called
women who don't work.

1:01:13.420 --> 1:01:16.131
Though they work longer, harder,
and for less pay

1:01:16.131 --> 1:01:18.091
-than any other class of worker.
-Gloria, I--

1:01:18.091 --> 1:01:21.219
I wanna write about
why women are 70 percent

1:01:21.219 --> 1:01:24.598
of the productive labor
in the world, paid and unpaid.

1:01:24.931 --> 1:01:27.017
Yet they own only one percent
of the property.

1:01:27.017 --> 1:01:28.143
-Are you finished?
-I wanna write about

1:01:28.643 --> 1:01:32.689
why masculinity means leading
and femininity means following,

1:01:32.689 --> 1:01:35.025
in the odd dance of daily life.

1:01:35.317 --> 1:01:36.359
[sighs, whistles]

1:01:37.110 --> 1:01:38.111
Well?

1:01:38.695 --> 1:01:40.363
Look, I'm sorry.

1:01:40.363 --> 1:01:42.574
But if I publish an article
saying women are equal,

1:01:42.574 --> 1:01:43.992
I'll have to publish one
side by side

1:01:43.992 --> 1:01:45.201
saying that they're not.

1:01:45.994 --> 1:01:46.995
It's not my opinion.

1:01:47.537 --> 1:01:49.873
But in journalism, as you know,
you got to be objective.

1:01:50.248 --> 1:01:52.334
Is that how you covered
the civil rights movement?

1:01:55.670 --> 1:01:59.674
[indistinct chatter]

1:02:11.436 --> 1:02:12.395
[woman] In ninth grade,

1:02:12.729 --> 1:02:14.814
our cheerleading coach
got my friend pregnant.

1:02:16.024 --> 1:02:17.734
He threatened to kill her
if she told.

1:02:20.779 --> 1:02:22.405
She borrowed money
from everyone.

1:02:23.239 --> 1:02:26.159
He wrote a check on her dad's
account to go to a, uh.

1:02:26.660 --> 1:02:27.869
An abortion doctor.

1:02:29.913 --> 1:02:31.081
But she didn't go.

1:02:32.916 --> 1:02:34.084
She got too scared...

1:02:35.168 --> 1:02:37.796
that he would tell someone
and her parents would find out.

1:02:39.756 --> 1:02:40.757
So, she...

1:02:44.052 --> 1:02:47.222
-She used a coat hanger.
-[woman gasps]

1:02:47.222 --> 1:02:49.182
[indistinct whispering]

1:02:54.646 --> 1:02:57.232
The next day, they found her
in the girls bathroom...

1:02:58.817 --> 1:02:59.734
dead.

1:03:02.320 --> 1:03:07.826
[train clacking]

1:03:08.159 --> 1:03:10.370
[baby coos]

1:03:11.621 --> 1:03:15.333
[speaks foreign language]

1:03:16.710 --> 1:03:18.294
You do not have any children?

1:03:22.132 --> 1:03:23.174
[speaks Hindi]

1:03:23.466 --> 1:03:24.467
Meaning husband.

1:03:27.637 --> 1:03:30.056
-No.
-Why no husband?

1:03:31.850 --> 1:03:34.269
[baby coughs, coos]

1:03:35.562 --> 1:03:37.772
[speaks Hindi]

1:03:37.772 --> 1:03:40.025
Congrats on your graduation,
kid. I'm so sorry

1:03:40.025 --> 1:03:41.026
I can't be there.

1:03:41.317 --> 1:03:42.569
[Gloria] It's okay.

1:03:43.737 --> 1:03:44.779
Mom will be there.

1:03:45.697 --> 1:03:47.907
Well, she sold the house to pay
for Smith College,

1:03:47.907 --> 1:03:49.784
you bet she'll be there. [sighs]

1:03:50.869 --> 1:03:52.078
She's very proud of you.

1:03:53.538 --> 1:03:54.748
I know.

1:03:54.748 --> 1:03:56.166
[indistinct chatter]

1:03:56.166 --> 1:03:58.209
Pop, how'd you convince her
to marry you?

1:04:00.420 --> 1:04:02.297
I told her it'll only take a
minute.

1:04:02.672 --> 1:04:05.091
[laughs] Where are you?

1:04:05.467 --> 1:04:08.094
[Leo] U.S. 95, Idaho.

1:04:08.094 --> 1:04:11.306
The annual Boise jam fair
starts tomorrow, crack of dawn.

1:04:13.391 --> 1:04:16.478
Hey, and how's that handsome
fiancé of yours?

1:04:16.478 --> 1:04:18.438
He seems like a good guy.
I like him.

1:04:19.064 --> 1:04:21.733
Maybe he's not as smart
as you are, but who is?

1:04:22.108 --> 1:04:23.318
Pop.

1:04:23.693 --> 1:04:24.819
So, when's the big day?

1:04:25.320 --> 1:04:27.447
You know, I'll be there
to walk you down the aisle,

1:04:27.447 --> 1:04:28.698
you can count on that.

1:04:31.034 --> 1:04:32.160
Actually, um...

1:04:32.952 --> 1:04:34.621
that's what I wanted
to talk to you about.

1:04:36.289 --> 1:04:38.625
I might have to postpone that.
[sighs]

1:04:39.084 --> 1:04:43.505
I got a fellowship to study
and-- and travel.

1:04:45.381 --> 1:04:47.217
Uh, someone's paying you
to travel?

1:04:47.884 --> 1:04:49.803
Very good. Where to?

1:04:50.470 --> 1:04:53.348
-India.
-Wow. India.

1:04:54.015 --> 1:04:55.892
About as far away
as you can get.

1:04:56.559 --> 1:04:58.603
So, you're not disappointed...
[laughs]

1:04:59.395 --> 1:05:00.522
...about the wedding?

1:05:03.733 --> 1:05:04.776
Hell no, Gloria.

1:05:05.318 --> 1:05:07.654
This opportunity is fantastic,
you can get married anytime.

1:05:11.574 --> 1:05:14.577
[clears throat] You let me know
when you get to Jaipur,

1:05:14.577 --> 1:05:16.788
because they have
superlative gems.

1:05:18.998 --> 1:05:20.792
You know,
I'll send along a money order.

1:05:22.502 --> 1:05:24.170
-Deal?
-Sure, Pop.

1:05:25.839 --> 1:05:27.173
[chuckles] Okay.

1:05:28.133 --> 1:05:29.217
Talk soon.

1:05:32.971 --> 1:05:33.972
Love you.

1:05:34.472 --> 1:05:36.432
-[telephone disconnects]
-Okay.

1:05:41.229 --> 1:05:42.188
[telephone dings]

1:05:56.035 --> 1:05:57.162
Are you all right, miss?

1:05:58.079 --> 1:06:00.290
Can I get you something?
Water, perhaps?

1:06:00.290 --> 1:06:02.876
No, um, I'm fine. Thank you.

1:06:12.135 --> 1:06:13.011
[grunts]

1:06:13.386 --> 1:06:17.140
[engine revving]

1:06:33.907 --> 1:06:35.283
So... [sighs]

1:06:36.618 --> 1:06:37.744
...how did you find my name?

1:06:39.162 --> 1:06:40.205
Through a friend.

1:06:40.997 --> 1:06:42.832
Oh, you're American.

1:06:42.832 --> 1:06:44.751
-[laughs]
-What are you doing in London?

1:06:45.376 --> 1:06:47.253
Waiting for a visa. [chuckles]

1:06:48.213 --> 1:06:50.340
I have a fellowship
to study in India.

1:06:50.340 --> 1:06:53.426
-Ah.
-It's a two-year fellowship.

1:06:55.553 --> 1:06:56.679
I see.

1:07:04.479 --> 1:07:05.772
I can't have this baby.

1:07:06.522 --> 1:07:08.900
I'm sorry, I'm--
I'm not married.

1:07:09.984 --> 1:07:11.027
I'm not ready.

1:07:12.237 --> 1:07:15.907
[exhales] And you are aware
that what you're asking

1:07:15.907 --> 1:07:18.952
isn't, strictly speaking, legal,
even here.

1:07:19.285 --> 1:07:21.120
Not unless it threatens
your life.

1:07:22.830 --> 1:07:23.915
I know.

1:07:25.333 --> 1:07:26.209
All right.

1:07:33.633 --> 1:07:35.218
You must promise me two things.

1:07:36.427 --> 1:07:37.428
First...

1:07:38.263 --> 1:07:40.098
you must not tell
anybody my name.

1:07:43.017 --> 1:07:44.060
Second...

1:07:45.436 --> 1:07:48.273
you will do what you want to do
with your life.

1:07:56.489 --> 1:07:57.824
Did I keep my promise?

1:08:08.418 --> 1:08:10.962
-[siren wailing]
-[horn honks]

1:08:10.962 --> 1:08:13.715
I was just at a speak out
about illegal abortion.

1:08:14.465 --> 1:08:15.508
I have to write about it.

1:08:16.384 --> 1:08:19.095
Gloria, you've worked so hard
to be taken seriously.

1:08:20.013 --> 1:08:22.265
You're saying,
this isn't a serious issue?

1:08:22.265 --> 1:08:23.975
-It's not what I said.
-If this magazine

1:08:23.975 --> 1:08:25.143
won't write about it,

1:08:25.143 --> 1:08:27.103
then I'm just gonna have
to speak about it.

1:08:27.103 --> 1:08:29.063
You can't associate yourself
with those crazy women.

1:08:32.233 --> 1:08:33.735
I just realized something.

1:08:34.902 --> 1:08:35.903
What?

1:08:36.612 --> 1:08:39.032
I am one of those crazy women.

1:08:44.912 --> 1:08:46.080
[woman] Hello.

1:08:46.080 --> 1:08:47.373
[crowd clapping] Hello.

1:08:47.623 --> 1:08:50.585
-I said, hello!
-[all cheer]

1:08:50.835 --> 1:08:52.295
Thank you for being here.

1:08:52.754 --> 1:08:55.048
My name
is Dorothy Pitman Hughes.

1:08:55.381 --> 1:08:56.883
And I have three children.

1:08:57.342 --> 1:08:58.885
Three children
that I love deeply.

1:08:59.469 --> 1:09:02.764
And the one thing I have noticed
is that too many women

1:09:03.014 --> 1:09:05.516
are being forced to leave
their children home alone

1:09:06.225 --> 1:09:09.062
while they work
to feed their families.

1:09:09.062 --> 1:09:12.482
We need childcare
and we need it now.

1:09:12.482 --> 1:09:14.150
[crowd agreeing]

1:09:14.442 --> 1:09:16.527
And here to join me
in the conversation

1:09:16.861 --> 1:09:18.112
is a new friend.

1:09:18.112 --> 1:09:19.614
She wanted to speak out today.

1:09:20.490 --> 1:09:24.035
-A journalist, Gloria Steinem.
-[woman] Okay.

1:09:24.410 --> 1:09:27.205
[indistinct chatter]

1:09:39.217 --> 1:09:43.179
Until recently, I wouldn't have
admitted the equality.

1:09:43.679 --> 1:09:45.973
So, the inequality
of my own life.

1:09:46.516 --> 1:09:49.519
Even though I was discriminated
against in journalism.

1:09:50.812 --> 1:09:54.065
Journalism which allows women
to write about women,

1:09:54.440 --> 1:09:56.901
and black people
to write about black people.

1:09:56.901 --> 1:09:59.904
But keeps editorial control in--

1:09:59.904 --> 1:10:00.905
[indistinct chatter]

1:10:01.280 --> 1:10:04.617
But keeps editorial control
in white male hands.

1:10:04.617 --> 1:10:06.202
[woman] I'll meet you there.

1:10:06.202 --> 1:10:07.203
But I'm--

1:10:07.829 --> 1:10:11.249
but I'm here to tell you that
the majority of the population

1:10:11.249 --> 1:10:13.668
cannot be
its second-class citizens.

1:10:14.585 --> 1:10:18.381
It didn't work in South Africa
and it can't work here.

1:10:18.381 --> 1:10:20.049
-[woman 1] South Africa?
-[woman 2] Really?

1:10:20.967 --> 1:10:22.677
[crowd agreeing]

1:10:23.886 --> 1:10:25.972
[Gloria] I have no idea
what I even said.

1:10:26.722 --> 1:10:29.142
It was like an out of body
experience.

1:10:29.142 --> 1:10:31.227
-You've never spoken before?
-No.

1:10:31.227 --> 1:10:33.271
I figured if no one
lets me write

1:10:33.271 --> 1:10:36.357
about the women's movement
I may have to speak about it.

1:10:37.608 --> 1:10:38.776
There's only one problem.

1:10:38.776 --> 1:10:39.819
-[sighs]
-What?

1:10:39.819 --> 1:10:41.904
I'm terrified
of public speaking.

1:10:41.904 --> 1:10:43.948
Well, that was obvious,
but I'm not.

1:10:44.782 --> 1:10:46.534
We'll get it together.
Don't worry about it.

1:10:48.119 --> 1:10:49.454
[wood clatters]

1:10:49.454 --> 1:10:50.997
[therapist] So,
what exactly happens

1:10:51.622 --> 1:10:53.416
before you speak in public?

1:10:53.666 --> 1:10:57.795
[chuckles] First my heart pounds
then my mouth goes dry.

1:10:57.795 --> 1:10:59.922
It feels sort of, like,
an Angora sweater

1:10:59.922 --> 1:11:01.382
is wrapped around each tooth.

1:11:01.382 --> 1:11:04.093
I'm worried about getting
to the end of each sentence

1:11:04.093 --> 1:11:05.970
without swallowing and...

1:11:07.221 --> 1:11:08.639
I think I'm going to die.

1:11:09.265 --> 1:11:11.392
[therapist] Hm.
Well, I think I can help.

1:11:12.226 --> 1:11:14.061
Writers usually have
the most trouble

1:11:14.061 --> 1:11:15.271
speaking in public,

1:11:15.271 --> 1:11:17.148
because they chose
a profession purposely

1:11:17.523 --> 1:11:20.443
in which they can communicate
without speaking.

1:11:21.110 --> 1:11:22.570
Well, writers and dancers.

1:11:22.945 --> 1:11:26.407
[indistinct chatter]

1:11:27.617 --> 1:11:29.535
-Are you okay?
-[exhales]

1:11:31.454 --> 1:11:32.413
Okay.

1:11:33.372 --> 1:11:34.707
[Gloria] I love dancing.

1:11:36.834 --> 1:11:37.752
[chuckles]

1:11:40.505 --> 1:11:43.299
I will confess that I have
a fear of public speaking.

1:11:44.217 --> 1:11:45.885
But what Dorothy
and I have to say

1:11:45.885 --> 1:11:48.054
is too important not to say it.

1:11:52.058 --> 1:11:53.518
Is there anyone else
in the audience

1:11:53.518 --> 1:11:55.436
also scared of public speaking?

1:11:55.895 --> 1:11:57.522
[audience laughing]

1:11:57.772 --> 1:11:59.273
-[indistinct chatter]
-Right.

1:11:59.941 --> 1:12:01.317
Thank you, um.

1:12:02.068 --> 1:12:05.821
Now, let's get
to the root cause here today.

1:12:06.489 --> 1:12:07.573
Reproductive rights,

1:12:08.032 --> 1:12:09.325
women need to decide...

1:12:09.325 --> 1:12:11.118
-[door opens]
-...the fate of our own bodies.

1:12:13.329 --> 1:12:15.706
[footsteps approaching]

1:12:16.624 --> 1:12:17.834
[indistinct whispering]

1:12:18.793 --> 1:12:20.711
All right. Everyone out
of the room immediately.

1:12:21.128 --> 1:12:23.256
-Come on, move it.
-[woman] Just go, go. Just go.

1:12:23.256 --> 1:12:24.340
[officer 1] Now!

1:12:24.340 --> 1:12:26.133
-He said there's a bomb.
-A bomb?

1:12:26.133 --> 1:12:27.593
-[officer 1] Wait outside.
-[Dorothy] From who?

1:12:27.593 --> 1:12:29.554
-[Gloria] I don't know.
-[indistinct chatter]

1:12:29.554 --> 1:12:30.638
[Gloria]
Apparently, they got a call

1:12:30.638 --> 1:12:31.722
from a Right to Lifer.

1:12:32.056 --> 1:12:34.100
It's just incredible
that those maniacs

1:12:34.100 --> 1:12:36.352
don't even see the irony
in threatening the lives

1:12:36.352 --> 1:12:37.603
-of all these people.
-[woman] I'm okay.

1:12:37.603 --> 1:12:39.814
-[officer 1] Hurry up.
-[officer 2] Let's go.

1:12:44.485 --> 1:12:46.237
[train clacking]

1:12:47.613 --> 1:12:51.409
The social and economic
revolution of the farm workers

1:12:51.409 --> 1:12:54.328
is well under way.
And it will not be stopped

1:12:54.328 --> 1:12:57.331
until we receive equality.

1:12:57.331 --> 1:12:59.834
And we don't wanna eat food
that was picked in poverty.

1:12:59.834 --> 1:13:02.336
And as fellow New Yorkers,
neither should you.

1:13:02.336 --> 1:13:05.423
We wanna thank Dolores Huerta
who has come from California

1:13:05.423 --> 1:13:06.674
to be with us here today.

1:13:06.966 --> 1:13:09.802
-We support the boycott!
-[Dolores] Thank you.

1:13:10.344 --> 1:13:12.847
There will be strikes
throughout this country

1:13:12.847 --> 1:13:15.182
because we have shown
what can be done.

1:13:15.558 --> 1:13:19.353
Every minute is a chance
to change the world.

1:13:19.645 --> 1:13:21.439
Can we change the world?

1:13:21.439 --> 1:13:22.481
-Yes, we can.
-[all agree]

1:13:27.987 --> 1:13:30.281
[speaking Spanish]

1:13:32.658 --> 1:13:35.161
I'll pitch an article
of the boycott to my editor.

1:13:35.578 --> 1:13:36.829
We'll get you a story out.

1:13:37.371 --> 1:13:38.331
[Dolores] You can try.

1:13:38.748 --> 1:13:39.915
But you know
orange juice companies

1:13:39.915 --> 1:13:41.626
advertise in magazines, right?
[chuckles]

1:13:42.835 --> 1:13:43.961
Don't waste your breath
just on print.

1:13:44.295 --> 1:13:45.463
Take it on the road.

1:13:46.547 --> 1:13:47.632
Keep talking.

1:13:49.175 --> 1:13:50.426
How are your kids?

1:13:51.427 --> 1:13:52.303
My kids...

1:13:53.429 --> 1:13:54.347
they're mad at me.

1:13:55.514 --> 1:13:56.515
I'm never home.

1:13:57.099 --> 1:14:01.228
Hm. I hear you. It's tough.
Let's just hope it's worth it.

1:14:04.023 --> 1:14:07.652
This year, the press has finally
discovered a movement

1:14:07.652 --> 1:14:10.988
that has already been strong
for several years now.

1:14:11.322 --> 1:14:15.785
And reported it as a small
privileged rather lunatic event

1:14:15.785 --> 1:14:18.329
instead of a major revolution
in consciousness.

1:14:18.329 --> 1:14:22.541
Everyone's consciousness. Male
and female, Black and white.

1:14:22.541 --> 1:14:23.417
This is the year

1:14:23.751 --> 1:14:26.796
-of women's liberation.
-[crowd cheering]

1:14:27.213 --> 1:14:30.424
University of Alabama,
Pennsville, October 12.

1:14:30.424 --> 1:14:33.469
Salem's College.
Bristol, Virginia on the 13th.

1:14:33.469 --> 1:14:34.845
Florida State University
on the 4th--

1:14:34.845 --> 1:14:36.472
[flight attendant] Could you
please not do that here?

1:14:36.472 --> 1:14:38.307
-Or go into the lavatory?
-That's obscene.

1:14:40.685 --> 1:14:43.145
Actually, refusing
to feed a child is obscene.

1:14:44.855 --> 1:14:45.815
Gloria.

1:14:47.233 --> 1:14:49.110
I'm not sure how--
how much longer

1:14:49.110 --> 1:14:50.194
I can keep doing this.

1:14:50.611 --> 1:14:52.530
-Breastfeed on planes?
-No.

1:14:53.197 --> 1:14:54.949
Deal with the stupidity
of white people?

1:14:55.908 --> 1:14:57.118
-Yes.
-[laughs]

1:14:58.035 --> 1:14:59.078
But no.

1:15:00.121 --> 1:15:01.706
Being on the road this much...

1:15:02.832 --> 1:15:04.125
it's hard on the kids and...

1:15:05.501 --> 1:15:08.629
and, um, I need to be at home
more next month.

1:15:08.629 --> 1:15:09.547
[baby coos]

1:15:10.089 --> 1:15:11.924
Do you think you can do
some of these talks without me?

1:15:13.092 --> 1:15:14.051
By myself?

1:15:15.010 --> 1:15:17.179
Well. No. Because...

1:15:18.764 --> 1:15:19.765
I have this friend...

1:15:21.183 --> 1:15:22.268
a civil rights lawyer.

1:15:23.185 --> 1:15:24.228
Flo Kennedy.

1:15:24.520 --> 1:15:27.481
A landlord is not allowed
to deny you housing

1:15:27.481 --> 1:15:29.275
because you are single.

1:15:29.275 --> 1:15:31.068
-That is some bullshit.
-[woman] Yes, Flo.

1:15:31.068 --> 1:15:33.028
[audience agreeing, clapping]

1:15:33.028 --> 1:15:34.196
Thank you.

1:15:34.822 --> 1:15:37.491
Being a mother
is a noble thing, right?

1:15:37.491 --> 1:15:39.118
-[all] Yes.
-So, why does it change

1:15:39.118 --> 1:15:42.496
when you put unwed
or welfare in front of it?

1:15:42.496 --> 1:15:43.748
-[audience clapping]
-No!

1:15:45.166 --> 1:15:46.876
-[audience exclaims]
-Shit.

1:15:47.752 --> 1:15:50.337
Listen to me, listen to me.
There are very few jobs

1:15:50.337 --> 1:15:53.674
that actually require a penis
or a vagina.

1:15:53.674 --> 1:15:54.925
[audience laughing]

1:15:54.925 --> 1:15:58.888
Every other job should be open
to everybody.

1:15:58.888 --> 1:16:02.641
-Everybody!
-[audience] Yeah.

1:16:05.352 --> 1:16:07.730
You need to make some noise.

1:16:07.730 --> 1:16:10.483
Rattle your cage, dog, cause
some trouble.

1:16:10.775 --> 1:16:13.194
You might not win right away,
but goddamn,

1:16:13.194 --> 1:16:15.696
you will have
a whole lot more fun.

1:16:15.696 --> 1:16:17.907
-[crowd cheering]
-Well.

1:16:18.491 --> 1:16:23.079
I wanna introduce you to my new
partner and cage rattler.

1:16:23.454 --> 1:16:25.372
-Gloria Steinem.
-[crowd cheering]

1:16:25.748 --> 1:16:26.749
Welcome her.

1:16:27.124 --> 1:16:29.668
[crowd exclaiming]

1:16:29.919 --> 1:16:31.170
[woman]
All right, all right, girl!

1:16:31.170 --> 1:16:32.546
[man] What are you, lesbians?

1:16:33.088 --> 1:16:34.715
What are you, the alternative?

1:16:38.552 --> 1:16:42.097
Oh, my God. Can I please
introduce you next time?

1:16:42.598 --> 1:16:45.267
It's such an anticlimax
if I speak after you.

1:16:45.267 --> 1:16:47.144
It wasn't as bad as all that.

1:16:47.144 --> 1:16:49.313
Just next time,
not so many statistics.

1:16:49.313 --> 1:16:51.106
You know, when you're laying
in a ditch

1:16:51.106 --> 1:16:52.817
with a truck on your ankle,

1:16:52.817 --> 1:16:54.443
you don't send somebody
to the library

1:16:54.443 --> 1:16:55.903
to find out how much it weighs.

1:16:57.279 --> 1:16:59.323
-You get it the hell off.
-[laughs]

1:16:59.740 --> 1:17:00.908
[Flo] Thank you.

1:17:01.951 --> 1:17:04.495
-[indistinct chatter]
-[car horn honking]

1:17:05.079 --> 1:17:07.748
I'm a loudmouth,
middle-aged, colored lady

1:17:07.748 --> 1:17:10.876
with a fused spine and three
feet of intestines missing.

1:17:10.876 --> 1:17:12.461
Now, a lot of people think
I'm crazy,

1:17:12.461 --> 1:17:13.462
-maybe you do, too,
-[laughs]

1:17:14.004 --> 1:17:16.924
but I never stop to wonder
why I'm not like other people.

1:17:17.216 --> 1:17:21.470
The mystery to me is
why more people aren't like me.

1:17:21.470 --> 1:17:22.555
What do you think?

1:17:25.057 --> 1:17:26.475
The book is outstanding.

1:17:28.352 --> 1:17:30.312
How'd you get the testimony
from all those women

1:17:30.312 --> 1:17:31.230
for the lawsuit?

1:17:32.189 --> 1:17:33.691
For once being a lawyer
didn't hurt.

1:17:34.316 --> 1:17:36.694
-And you got it published.
-Mm-hmm.

1:17:36.694 --> 1:17:38.070
Amazing. [chuckles]

1:17:39.655 --> 1:17:42.992
I like the title, Abortion Rap.

1:17:44.243 --> 1:17:46.245
Was that yours or Diane's?

1:17:46.245 --> 1:17:48.289
[indistinct radio chatter]

1:17:49.206 --> 1:17:52.084
[man on radio]
...which is 88 to 77.

1:17:52.084 --> 1:17:54.628
In a jockacratic society,
you can turn on the radio

1:17:54.628 --> 1:17:57.506
and hear every goddamn
basketball score in this country

1:17:57.506 --> 1:17:59.842
repeated all day long.

1:18:00.175 --> 1:18:04.096
You never hear how many women
die of illegal abortions.

1:18:05.014 --> 1:18:06.974
I tell you, if men
could get pregnant,

1:18:07.224 --> 1:18:09.268
abortion would be a sacrament.

1:18:09.643 --> 1:18:11.979
["Too Many Days" playing]

1:18:13.522 --> 1:18:15.983
[indistinct chanting]

1:18:18.777 --> 1:18:22.907
♪ Monday you left me
Standing in the rain, yes ♪

1:18:23.532 --> 1:18:26.285
♪ Tuesday it seemed to
Close your eyes to my heart ♪

1:18:26.285 --> 1:18:28.037
[officer] You gotta stay
on the street.

1:18:28.037 --> 1:18:29.955
♪ But another day must come ♪

1:18:29.955 --> 1:18:32.374
♪ And go
And I know ♪

1:18:32.374 --> 1:18:37.213
♪ That it can't be this slow ♪

1:18:38.255 --> 1:18:39.840
[reporter 1] Gloria,
can you address

1:18:39.840 --> 1:18:42.301
this new term,
sexual harassment

1:18:42.301 --> 1:18:44.428
and whether you've ever
experienced it?

1:18:44.720 --> 1:18:47.723
And, Flo, could you talk about
racism in America?

1:18:50.601 --> 1:18:53.646
I just wanna point out that
you directed a question to me

1:18:53.646 --> 1:18:55.731
about universal womanhood
and to Flo

1:18:55.731 --> 1:18:57.316
about the condition
of being black.

1:18:57.983 --> 1:19:00.444
Do you think Flo is unable
to answer a question

1:19:00.444 --> 1:19:01.987
about the condition
of being a woman?

1:19:03.364 --> 1:19:05.699
Ms. Kennedy, what do you
have to say about that?

1:19:07.660 --> 1:19:10.287
When you've experienced
bullshit in one form,

1:19:10.287 --> 1:19:12.164
you're more likely to recognize
it in another.

1:19:13.499 --> 1:19:15.542
Racism and sexism
are intertwined.

1:19:15.542 --> 1:19:17.920
They cannot be
uprooted separately.

1:19:17.920 --> 1:19:19.880
[people clapping]

1:19:19.880 --> 1:19:23.217
Ms. Steinem, a lot of people say
your looks are why people

1:19:23.217 --> 1:19:25.844
listen to you,
not what you have to say.

1:19:28.430 --> 1:19:30.474
-Is that a question?
-[reporter 2] Oh, yeah.

1:19:30.474 --> 1:19:32.434
[woman] Don't worry, Gloria,
it's important for someone

1:19:32.434 --> 1:19:33.894
who can play the game and win

1:19:34.186 --> 1:19:36.313
to say the game
isn't worth shit.

1:19:36.313 --> 1:19:37.648
[Flo laughing]

1:19:38.649 --> 1:19:40.776
-Have you ever been married?
-No. Uh-huh.

1:19:43.404 --> 1:19:46.281
-That's all?
-Yeah, well, next question.

1:19:46.865 --> 1:19:48.284
Zoom in camera one and two.

1:19:49.159 --> 1:19:50.035
[Gloria] Why not?

1:19:50.494 --> 1:19:51.620
-[host] All right.
-Is that your next question?

1:19:51.620 --> 1:19:52.538
[host] Why not?

1:19:54.123 --> 1:19:54.999
I don't know.

1:19:55.708 --> 1:19:56.834
[chuckles]

1:19:58.252 --> 1:19:59.920
But do you ever
wanna be married?

1:20:01.755 --> 1:20:03.298
Eventually, but, um...

1:20:04.216 --> 1:20:08.012
it keeps receding two years
in a comfortable distance.

1:20:11.015 --> 1:20:12.808
